# Define Privacy, Access, and Publication Boundaries

## Resolution (2026-07-12, grilled with Joel)

1. **Access**: tailnet membership IS the auth. Single tier, every tailnet
   device reads everything, no app-level auth, no device ACL. All nine nodes
   are `joelhooks@`; the joelclaw subdomains remain Joel-only surfaces even
   if broader access arrives someday.
2. **Redaction is presentation, not just data hygiene** (Joel's charter:
   "redaction could be a style"). Two layers. Data at rest always safe:
   secrets/tokens never persisted, third-party content only as bounded
   redact.ts excerpts, hard exclusions (sensitive/captures/people/
   family-health) never rendered. Presentation: **secure mode by default**
   (PII spans masked — blur/half-revealed); a floating **JoelClaw toolbar**
   (left edge, feature flags) flips reveal mode for the current session,
   auto-reverting. Reveal can only un-mask what's stored. Driver: readership
   is Joel-only at the network layer but not at the pixel layer — he records
   screen-share YouTube videos on these machines; default pixels must be
   safe to leak. Toolbar mechanics land in `decide-brain-svx-rendering-model`.
3. **Audit**: none. No view/reveal logs — single-reader theater. ClickHouse
   exists for *general* event streams (build/system observability) whenever
   useful; that's telemetry, not privacy machinery.
4. **Retention**: indefinite by default.
5. **Deletion**: privacy scrub is the one chartered exception to edition
   immutability — edit the snapshot under `data/editions/`, rebuild, leave a
   one-line tombstone ("excerpt removed <date>"). Git history is the audit
   trail; rewriting it is allowed only as a named deliberate act.
   *(Recommended, unobjected — Joel can amend.)*

Unblocks `decide-brain-svx-rendering-model` (toolbar + privacy-key contract
now defined).

## Grilling notes (2026-07-12, in progress)

- **Access/readership (decided)**: single tier, tailnet-wide read, no
  app-level auth, no device ACL needed. It's Joel-only right now; all nine
  tailnet nodes are `joelhooks@`. Even if access opens up later, the
  joelclaw subdomains used this way remain Joel's personal surfaces.
  Tailnet membership IS the auth.
- **Redaction as presentation (decided)**: two layers. DATA layer keeps the
  AGENTS.md contract verbatim — secrets/tokens never persisted, third-party
  content stored only as bounded redacted excerpts via redact.ts, hard
  exclusions (sensitive/captures/people/family-health) never rendered.
  PRESENTATION layer: pages default to **secure mode** (PII spans masked —
  blur/half-revealed); a floating JoelClaw toolbar (left edge, feature
  flags) flips **reveal mode** for the current session (session-scoped,
  auto-reverts). Reveal can only un-mask what's stored — secrets are
  unrevealable because they're never stored. Rationale: readership is
  Joel-only at the network layer but NOT at the pixel layer — he now records
  screen-share YouTube videos on these machines; default pixels must be
  safe to leak. Toolbar/flag mechanics belong to the rendering-model
  ticket; the CONTRACT (safe-at-rest data, mask-by-default, session reveal)
  is this ticket's boundary.

## Question

Who and what may access the primary wiki from Flagg, the fleet, Joel's phone, and remote environments; how are private work streams separated from redacted public-safe projections; and what authentication, audit, retention, and deletion boundaries are required before Slack, Front, Gmail, Discord, and session evidence can appear together?
